  "nursesNote": "Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia) is a chronic, milder depression with a low mood most days for at least two years; the person usually keeps functioning but feels persistently down. Seasonal affective disorder (SAD) is depression in a seasonal pattern, usually fall and winter, with fatigue, oversleeping, carbohydrate craving, and weight gain. The nurse still assesses suicide risk directly, since any depression carries risk. SAD is treated with bright light therapy (using a light box for about 30 minutes in the morning) along with SSRIs and increased natural light and activity. Dysthymia is treated with therapy (CBT) and SSRIs, which take weeks to work. The nurse encourages routine, exercise, and follow-up.",
